193. numerata, common with sums of money in the sense ‘counted,' i.e. ‘paid in cash,' e. g. Trin. 965, Pseud. 1149, Pers. 5²4·

On the distinction between nume- rare and adnumerare (v. 501) see Langen (Beitr'aigffi pp. 93—95). ‘Two talents paid down into my hand’ is named as an impossibly large sum in grim joke.

195. ina alio ibit tamen, ‘ Phi- laenium shall go to some one else all the same.’ Plautus is fond of keeping tamen till the last place in the line and sentence. See on Epid. 426.

196. ubi illaec quae dedi ante? Sunt omitted, as osten in such questions. Cf. sed quidhoc? and Men. 281 ubi conuiuae ceteri ? with Brix's note.
